<p>Angiotensin is a substance produced by the body to maintain blood pressure when it binds to its receptors in body tissues. When angiotensin binds to receptors found in blood vessels, it causes the vessels to constrict. This causes an increase in blood pressure.</p>
<p>Under normal circumstances, this mechanism ensures normal blood flow. In people with high blood pressure, this mechanism provides an opportunity to decrease blood pressure. When losartan binds to angiotensin receptors, it leaves no space for angiotensin to bind.</p>
